==English==

===Etymology===
Compound of ''[[bung]]'' + ''[[starter]]''.

===Alternative spellings===
* [[bung starter]]

===Noun===
{{en-noun-reg}}

#A [[tool]] for opening [[barrel]]s by removing the [[bung]].
#*'''1914:''' [[w:O. Henry|O. Henry]], ''Heart of the West'', "Doubleday, Page & company, for Review of reviews co", page 133 - But he had not yet learned to estimate these cool, languid, Southwestern knights of the '''bungstarter''', who had the manners of an Earl of Pawtucket, ...
#*'''1929:''' [[w:John Russell|John Russell]], ''Color of the East'', "W. W. Norton", page 229 - The Portuguese equivalent of '''bungstarter''' whiffed Angus Jones by an eyelash.
#*'''1941:''' [[w:Clark Barnaby Firestone|Clark Barnaby Firestone]], ''Flowing South'', "National Travel Club", page 138 - "That's where the barkeeper took a '''bungstarter''' and killed a man who was shooting wild."
#*'''1943:''' [[w:Ernest Thompson Seton|Ernest Thompson Seton]], ''The Preacher of Cedar Mountain'', "The Seton village press", page 134 - "Pat, let me have that keg," and the schoolteacher proceeded to hammer around the bung, in the way of the orthodox '''bungstarter'''.

